    <svcproc id="hl0500406" svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="6">
        <title>PITMAN ARM</title>
        <para>When the pitman arm is , the timing arrows on the arm and the output shafts must be aligned. If the pitman
            arm has two timing arrows marked "L" and "R," the same arm is used on both the master and the slave gear.
            The "L" arrow is used on the left or master gear and the "R" arrow is used on the right or slave gear (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f05004b2">Figure 112</hotlnk>).
        </para>
        <figure id="f05004b2" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g05004b2" filename="../figg05/G05004B2.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 112. Align Timing Arrows When Installing Pitman Arm</caption>
        </figure>
        <para>The following charts detail the various pitman arm installation methods offered by the Sheppard Company.
        </para>
        <para>Follow these procedures for the attachment method you are working with. Correct torque values are very
            important. Use the lubricant where indicated.
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>If the pitman arm is not applied to the
                    <hotlnk document="s05004_51.xml" xrefid="hl0500404">torque specifications
                        <xref refid="hl0500404"/>
                    </hotlnk>
                    , the pitman arm could work loose. If this situation is found, inspect both the pitman arm and the
                    output shaft for spline wear. If either part is worn, replace necessary parts.
                </para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>Do not weld arm or shaft.</para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
